Are you ready for the X-Challenge?

Challenge your friends to solve this simple puzzle and wait to see their faces when you reveal the mind-blowing solution.

  • The goal is simple, separate the two bars.
  • The solution is going to BLOW your mind, trust me, nobody is going to figure it out.

Printing parameters:

  • The 4x bars must be printed with a inFill > 90%.
  • No support needed.

SOLUTION (DONT READ IT IF YOU WANT TO TRY FIRST):
The X is locked by 4 hidden bars (one in each side). Every move you make is moving the bars at the center and making it impossible to separate the blocks.
Have you ever heard of centrifugal force?
That's right! The only posible way to unlock the X is......to spin it!
Just put it on a table, spin it and separate it!
But shhhh keep it a secret.
Once you have blocks(2x) and bars printed, you have to put one bar inside the small block, and then use glue on that small block to stick it parallel with the long block.
NGSS
Centrifugal Force This puzzle will only be resolved using centrifugal force, so it's a good approach to see how it works.

Activity about Centrifugal Force First give the puzzle to the student and challenge him to resolve it.
Later, the teacher explain to the student how the centrifugal force works and ask him to try again.
If the student doesn't get to resolve it, the teacher can unblock and separate the pieces of the puzzle to show him how it works.

Step 1: Mount the silicone bumpers

I suggest to apply 5 silicone bumpers beneath the base piece, so it will be more stable on the desk. You can use bumpers with a diameter up to 20mm.

Step 2: Assemble the PCB holders

The central part of the base consists of 4 sliding pieces arranged in a cross along which can be moved the anchoring blocks to firmly keep the printed circuit board in place. The assembly of the PCB holders to the base piece requires some wing nuts (5mm) and Hex bolts (5×12 mm). The PCB holders have two faces, one for straight sides, the other for the corners of a printed circuit board. You can choose the right face simply turning the holder.

Step 3: Assemble the crane arms

Fit the vertical crane arm into the hole of the rotating base support, then mount the horizontal crane arm using a wing nut (5mm) and a Hex bolt (5×12 mm).

Step 4: Install micro sprung probes

The horizontal crane arm ends with a clamp to fit a micro sprung probe
(http://uk.rs-online.com/web/p/needle-point-probes/0775726).

Step 5: Add optional parts

Now that you have almost finished your customized "PCB Workstation" perhaps you would like to add a magnifying glass, or a LED lamp, or even other accessories available from my original project "PCB Workstation with Articulated Arms" (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:801279).

description.text:
I made this for a demo at the Institute of Contemporary Arts in London. Using some trickery, a MakerBot first-generation Replicator can print this in an hour and 15 minutes (!)
As it's quick and only uses 14g of PLA, it's a great way to turn bits of leftover filament into xmas decorations.
It's designed to print as just a shell, with no internal or external support material-- the model has a couple of built-in props and struts which can be cut off after printing.

The STL file has built-in minimal supports, and some cunning trickery to help it print without collapsing. It is designed to print with no support, no raft, no infill and single wall thickness.
In MakerWare (for example) you will need to create a custom profile, and edit the following values:
layerHeight: 0.25
numberOfShells: 1
roofLayerCount: 2
floorLayerCount: 2
doRaft: false
doSupport: false
...plus whatever other settings you'd normally use for PLA (I doubt this could work with ABS). To avoid stringiness, I also increased retractDistance to 2.0, and tweaked feedDiameter to get the flow rate exactly right.

La direction et la partie AV sont aussi refaites pour pouvoir monter une pelle ou une fraise dans le futur.

title: zwHolder — Filament Holder for FlashForge Creator Pro printer

description.text:
Recently I have started working on FlashForge Creator Pro printer. There is everything included in the set, even original filament holder. Unfortunately during the whole printing process I almost used all filament attached to the printer itself, so there was a high time to buy some. I got very interested in DevilDesing filaments offer, especially their starter packs where you get 6 most popular colors in small 0.33 kg spools. After placing an order I have found out that the diameter of spools doesn't match original filaments holders and they need to be an exact fit. Because of the different size it would be impossible for spool to rotate freely and move the filament to the extruder. I decided to create my own solution using my 3D printer instead to solve this issue.

This is how I measured, designed and printed my new filament holders — zwHolder for Creator Pro. During design process I found a few problems:

  • it must fit to the original mounting points on the printer,
  • spool should rotate freely on the holder so it needs to have round shape,
  • it would be great to have a possibility to print it without supporters - this determines the orientation on printer table,
  • it would be great not to print things that are not required, so needed to remove elements that don’t have any functionality.
    If you compare my requirements with the current model you can see that it meets all the expectations.

Project was created using AutoDesk Fusion 360. Final object was printed using FlashPrint from FlashForge slicer using red color PLA filament from DevilDesing.

description.text:
This is a light-box for a mechanical televisor. See the NBTV forum at https://www.taswegian.com/NBTV/forum/ to delve into that hobby.

There are two parts - the box and the lid. They are side by side so they can be printed flat. The box has a curved aperture window which is exactly the right arc shape for whatever Nipkow disk dimensions you enter as the parameters. It has a bit of a tolerance too, so you can get it to display a bit more than a frame in size. Inside the box are a number of shelves; these are to hold the plastic diffuser sheets (if you want them). Each "layer" on each shelf would be glued onto the shelf so it holds firm. Finally, although the backplate is snap-fit (should be really tight), I've put a screwdriver notch in the base so that you can leverage it off. The shelf inside prevents light entering/escaping through that slot. For wire entry/exit, just drill holes where you want 'em.

I will be modifying this thing as I iron out the design bugs, but the latest version will always be here.

17/2 New version uses a new style of lid so that there's no obstruction to inserting exact-sized circuit board.

title: Wall-Mounted Multiple Backdrop Paper Roll Pulldown Rack

description.text:
This is a multi-paper pull-down mount for photography backplates that includes a locking mechanism to lock the paper in place. Mine is currently holding 4' rolls of paper.

Extra parts required:

  • 5' (foot), 1/2" (inch) PVC pipe x3 Link: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00MNIXTY6/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

  • Super Glue
  1. Print everything out.
  2. Measure the length of your paper roll and mount the main brackets on the wall, making sure to give enough space to fit the paper roll, guide and "star" locking mechanism plus a little extra space (maybe about an inch or more).
  3. Slide the PVC pipes into place (IF YOUR PAPER ROLLS FIT NICELY ONTO THE PVC PIPES, PLACE THEM ON NOW), make sure that you slide a star and guide onto each PVC pipe in between the two brackets.
  4. place the handles on whichever side you want to control the paper rolls on.
  5. Once you confirm that there is enough space for the paper, stars, guides and a little bit of sliding room, super glue the stars, guides and handles into place.
  6. (IF YOUR PAPER ROLL FITS NICELY OVER THE PVC PIPES, SKIP THIS STEP) Place your paper roll below the whole setup, bring the cut side of the paper roll up to one of the PVC pipes.
  7. Tape or glue the paper to the PVC pipe and roll it till the amount of paper reaches the 3D printed "Guide."

You're done! Now you can roll the paper out and slide the PVC pipe (using the handle) to lock it into place. The "star" 3d print on the PVC pipe will lock into bracket with the star cut-outs.

I included some sample photos I took using the white backplate.

description.text:
I had a lot of trouble getting the 0.5 version of the base plate printed.  I tried sending off to ShapeWays and Ponoko both of which complained of wall thickness problems at the bearing pole and at the filament feed blocks.  This is my humble and crude attempt at a fix.  The holes for the filament and the bearing pole do require you to drill them out (I could not be sure what screw sizes would work so I didn't make them too large).  I also left off the T-Slot at the top of the larger filament guide block (what is that for, BTW?).  
An improvement to this would be to make the bearing movable and spring loaded to allow you to adjust the compression on the passing filament.  It's also a prelude to being able to handle 3mm filament when the time comes.  Any input would be much appreciated.  This printed on my Solidoodle with .3mm resolution without incident.  
UPDATE: I added a version with the bearing supports embedded.  I will shortly add one more part that effectively reduces the parts count to 11.  
UPDATE (again): In staying faithful to Serge's design, I put the T-Slot back in the latest version of this thing, but I've left all the other versions there to allow you to choose and do your own evolution.  
UPDATE (yet again):  It just bothered me that the bearing for the extruder was on a fixed mount and that it could not withstand the forces on it too much, so I cobbled this crude modification.  The bearing mount is now its own part.  Insert a small spring between it and the LM8UU bearing mount and pass an M2.5 or M3 or equivalent long screw with a nut on the bearing mount.  If you use a screw slightly larger than the hole there, you will tap the hole and be able to adjust the tension on the filament and support multiple filament sizes.  You might need to superglue the nut on the bearing mount to handle the forces being applied.  If anyone has any ideas, please pass them along.  Another idea is to put a spring on either side of the bearing mount and put a small washer and nut on the OTHER side of the bearing mount allowing the bearing mount to be under tension but also 'float' in its slot, which should help cushion some of the forces against the mount.  
Printing note: So I found I made 2 small errors (ok, not that small for some).  First, if you look at the versions with the build in mounts, you will see 2 holes have disappeared.  I'll need to put those back in at some point.  The second error is in the protrusion for the filament that has the T-slot in it.  I will need to cut off a piece of it at the top of the circle where it is to allow my bearing to fit.  To get your bearing to sit, file a little of the pillar for it and with a piece of flat stock (like a paint stirrer), hammer in the bearing.  Once in, it will never move again as it is effectively press fit.  Finally, if you are worried that the layers are put down in the Z-axis and cannot withstand tensile forces, get some LIQUID superglue and slather it all over the surface of this thing and let it cure overnight.  The glue will make a tough shell that also will hold all the layers fast.  If it works for my model rockets, it works for this.  
Build Update: A photo of the assembled base is included here and you can see the base plate and the Y plate together. Obviously, I don't intent to make my bed that big, but I know that if I wanted to, I could.  
Final Update: In response to one request, I re-added the missing 2 holes I had inadvertently covered.  On my print, I could still see their outline (I print ABS only) so I had drilled mine out.  In this I put in 4mm holes.  If they are narrow, simply widen them with your trusty drill.

Inspired by the parameterised Wells Turbine posted by Parkinbot (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:224320), here is a parameterised impulse turbine with guide vanes designed to give unidirectional rotation in bi-directional air flows, such as air flows generated by an oscillating water column (OWC). The guide vanes and turbine buckets of this model were inspired by papers in the literature by Antonio Falcao and others.
This is my first attempt at an OpenSCAD model, so hopefully it's not too embarrassing! At the start of the code are a number of variables to control the number of buckets and guide vanes, the radius of the turbine, the radius of the inner hole through the assembly, the thickness of the various ribs and rims, the number and size of some cut-outs in the rib of the turbine to reduce weight, and the height of the vanes.
There are also three variables which switch 'on or off' the three pieces in the drawing so that they may be individually exported for printing.
The profiles of the buckets, guide vanes and guide vane hubs are described as a set of points in the relevant modules, so to change the profiles, you could change these points.

description.text:
This is a improvement for the Anet A6 feeder to allow flexible filament to be easly printed.
As flexible filament tends to bend and stuck the feeding toothed wheel, it needs to be precisely guided to the hot end, without letting any hole where it could escape.
So I desined this parts which I use for many month with any filament, flexible or not : no more feeding troubles !
As the goal is to have no hole at all on the feeding path, the "Filament guide.stl" part need to be manually adjusted :

  • path drilled with a D.2mm drill for good filament slide
  • Mobile throated wheel hole need to be adjusted (with a Dremel) -> the throated wheel (the one mounted on the "Pusher.stl" part) must just touch the toothed wheel (mounted on the motor), allowing good strong feeding. Manage needed adjustement by assembling both wheel on the part. Test stengh by inserting a PLA or ABS filament in the path hole, you must feel it grip well without slicing.
    Finally, when adjusted and set, you don't need to worry no more for many many many hours of printing (I just made one of theses parts which still work after few hundred hours of printing).

N.B : "Filament tensor.stl" is not needed for the feeder to work. The aim of this part is to pull the filament from the spool (the pull force is obtained while this part is bending), avoiding the filament to bend too much (or to strech in case of flexible filament). Work well ;-)

comments.text: This was one of my first mods for my A8. I bought my machine in December 2017 and there was a slight fitment issue with relation to the LCD mounting holes. The left brace was about 1 mm too short along the x-axis (distance from LCD holes to acrylic frame upright support), and the right brace was about 1mm too long in the x-axis which caused the piece to cover the acrylic frame holes for the upright support and not fit without modification. I was able to fix this by drilling 1/4" (6.35mm) holes for the LCD mounts on the right brace which gave enough room to mount the brace to the LCD holes and the right side upright. I haven't done any test prints yet, but frame rigidity up top is definitely improved. Great work!

title: State of Ohio shape with lettering for Dual Extruder

description.text: I created this as practice for dual extruding. Included are two .stl files, one with the State outline and the other with the lettering infill. The .stl files are 3mm thick by default, but I've included the Sketchup drawing files if you want to adjust this thickness.

Printer:

Multec M420 with 2Move

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Step 1: Obtain shapefile

Download US states shapefile and load into TileMill or other similar program

Step 2: Export shapefile to SVG

Use TileMill to export SVG of desired area (in this case the shape of Ohio)

Step 3: Cleanup SVG file and add text

Edit and simplify the path using Inkscape. Trim any undesired areas surrounding the border outline. Add text (OHIO in this case)

Step 4: Convert to .STL

Use the following online converter to convert the file from an SVG to .STL
http://svg2stl.com/

Note, this converter cannot handle very complex shapes. I'm looking for a better way to perform this step or another route to import into Sketchup.

Step 5: Cleanup file in Sketchup and split into two files for dual extrusion

Delete unnecessary edges and flatten to 2D image. Save file and create a duplicate. Edit one file to be lettering only and the other to be background. Note, do not move the shapes or polygons after splitting into two files. The origin needs to be preserved in the same relative location so that the two .stl files can be aligned in your slicer program.

Step 6: Set height in CAD program and export to .stl

Extrude both drawings to the desired height and use a 3rd party extension to export each drawing as an STL file.

Step 7: Import files into slicer software, align and print

Import your two .stl files into your slicer software. Because we were careful to maintain the position of the origin in each file, we can simply align the origins of the .stl files and print after assigning the appropriate processes to each file.
